[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(15) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "The young lions roared . . .",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The real answer to the question, that Israel had forsaken its true master, is given in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 2:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Here it is implied in the description of what the runaway slave had suffered. Lions had attacked him; not figuratively only, as symbolising invaders, but in the most literal sense, they had made his land waste (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Kings 17:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Are burned.—Better, levelled with the ground.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Are burned.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Better, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "levelled with the ground.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
